    Development Notes

    Updated notes 21.10.16

    - PNG fallback fix for older browsers

    - Color class update to ease custom coloring of components

    - Updates to global headers and footers with new elements such as search bar


    Updated notes 14.10.16

    - Pending change to JavaScript to disable the carousel on dashboard-landing page in mobile and tablet sized viewports - we'll add JavaScript globally to control at what breakpoints JavaScript functions are run

    - Pending change to tabs to incorporate breakpoint behaviour changes based on the same JavaScript change above.


    Updated notes 4.10.16

    All global HTML components updated

    Dashboard logged in menu state active

    Subnav in play, triggered by selecting an primary nav item. This is currently set to toggle and needs a follow up course of action to determine how this is tied into the back end. Currently we have a "subnav-active" class added to the BODY tag, so when a new page is landed upon, we can set this as a flag to determine whether it's visible. TBC.

    Charts now animating in cn06

    We now have IE9 support. There will be slight degredation but modules will retain gutters and equal height columns for desktop view.

    We are now using CSS flexbox for grid layout with IE9 for fallback

    CORE notes

    As per Front End deliverables for Gen2, we are utilising a 12 column grid via Bootstrap v3.

    HEADER - Desktop and Mobile header + navigation built. Logged out state. Subnav TBC but this will sit outside the *HEADER* HTML tag.

    COMPONENTS - Each component is encapuslated by a *SECTION* tag, each with specific classes which are mandatory. Some are global and some are component specific. Heights of component need to be resolved.

    All HTML mark up contained within each *SECTION* should be accounted for.

    SECTION classes that begin with "module-outer", "module-bleed") etc. determine margin and padding both internally and externally are mandatory for layout. A full list of these module types will be provided in further code drops.

    Component specific styles (eg. "cn03__v1"). These determine color and styles specific to that particular module as outlined in design. Utilising these classes helps ensure modules not to deviate from established designs. If a component does not have a variant class, certain specific styles will be missing. This MAY affect layout, but the intention is to keep this aethetic.

    Component layout and structure must stay fixed, however content within each singular component can of course be changed as needed.

    Headings. For all components containing headings - where a heading exists outside and above of a module which contains a row of border style components, that heading is optional.

    For equal height cols, ensure the postfix on "row" class includes the appropriate designation. So, div class="row row-eq-height-md" where any child cols have a "md" designation. div class="row row-eq-height-sm" where child cols have a "sm" designation.
